'''GlobaLex''' is an online publication of the Hauser Global Law School Program at the [[New York University School of Law]] providing research tools for [[comparative law]], [[international law]], and the laws of various jurisdictions around the world. It was launched in 2005 by editor-in-chief Mirela Roznovschi, then NYU Law School's Foreign and International Law Reference Librarian, with the support of professor [[Joseph H. H. Weiler]] and dean [[Richard Revesz]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://scholarship.law.cornell.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://duckduckgo.com/&httpsredir=1&article=1069&context=ijli|first=Heidi Frostestad|last=Kuehl|title=GlobaLex: A Unique and Valuable Tool for International Law Research|journal=International Journal of Legal Information|volume=34|issue=3|date=2006|accessdate=April 24, 2018|ref=harv|page=474}}</ref> Roznovschi conceived of the project while in [[Armenia]] as a guest instructor in [[legal research]], and in 2003 after her return to NYU, she discussed the idea with Weiler, who came up with the name.<ref name="Ford">{{cite news|url=https://www.asil.org/sites/default/files/ILRIG_Informer_Issue_2012.pdf|first=Don|last=Ford|title=Happy Birthday GlobaLex|magazine=International Legal Research Informer|issue=Winter|year=2012|accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref>
GlobaLex publishes articles both on topical areas, such as treaty research (particularly ''[[travaux préparatoires]]''), regional trade agreements in Africa, or the [[TRIPS Agreement]], as well as guides to the laws of specific jurisdictions.<ref>{{harvnb|Kuehl|2006|p=474}}</ref> By 2007, GlobaLex had coverage of more than 80 jurisdictions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/spectrum/archives/Vol-11/pub_sp0706/pub-sp0706-guides.pdf|first=Mimi|last=Vollstedt|title=Guides for the World: GlobaLex offers a simple, yet rich, web site of foreign, comparative, and international law guides|magazine=AALL Spectrum|date=June 2007|accessdate=April 24, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421173335/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/spectrum/archives/Vol-11/pub_sp0706/pub-sp0706-guides.pdf|archivedate=April 21, 2016|ref=harv|page=18}}</ref> By 2012, that had expanded to a total of 195 research guides, including 144 guides for specific jurisdictions, 15 comparative law guides, and 32 international law guides.<ref name="Ford"/> As editor-in-chief, Roznovschi was responsible for finding authors who are experts in their topic areas to write guides to specific jurisdictions or topic areas, and to supervise the process of writing the article. Some authors write a guide in a foreign language and have it translated into English, with the whole process often taking as long as a year. GlobaLex pays a small honorarium to authors to offset basic expenses.<ref>{{harvnb|Vollstedt|2007|p=19}}</ref> In 2017, Lucie Olejnikova replaced Roznovschi as editor-in-chief following the retirement of the latter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slaw.ca/2018/01/24/new-developments-in-international-legal-information-resources/|first=Lyonette|last=Louis-Jacques|title=New Developments in International Legal Information Resources|magazine=Slaw: Canada's Online Legal Magazine|date=January 24, 2018|accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref>
Because of GlobaLex's breadth, [[law librarian]]s frequently recommend it as a valuable resource for legal research.<ref>{{harvnb|Kuehl|2006|p=482}}</ref> Some commenters in 2007 noted that the depth of coverage varied greatly by jurisdiction and that greater standardization would be helpful.<ref>{{harvnb|Vollstedt|2007|p=19}}</ref> A 2016 review evaluated GlobaLex favorably under [[information search process]] criteria, though criticized it for its lack of current awareness tools.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Xiaomeng Alex|last=Zhang|title=A tale of two resources: Foreign Law Guide v. Globalex|journal=Reference Reviews|volume=30|issue=5|date=2016|doi=10.1108/RR-09-2015-0224}}</ref> Roznovschi was the recipient of the [[American Association of Law Libraries]]' Reynolds & Flores Award in 2015 for her work on GlobaLex.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aallnet.org/fcilsis/awards-grants/reynolds-flores-publication-award/|title=The Thomas H. Reynolds and Arturo A. Flores FCIL-SIS Publications Award|publisher=American Association of Law Libraries|accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref>
