[[File:Zona Arqueológica de Yohualichan.JPG|thumb|Archaeological zone of Yohualichan]]
'''Yohualichan''' (''Yohualican'' or ''House of Night'' in [[Nahuatl]]) is a [[Pre-Columbian era|Pre-Columbian]] archaeological site located in [[Cuetzalan del Progreso (municipality)|Cuetzalan del Progreso]] in the Mexican state of [[Puebla]].

Yohualican and the larger nearby city of [[El Tajín]] both reached a cultural and political epoch during the [[Classic period]] and are both believed to have been constructed and populated by the [[Totonac people]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.inah.gob.mx/zonas/114-zona-arqueologica-de-yohualichan|title=Zona Arqueológica de Yohualichan|website=www.inah.gob.mx|language=es-es|access-date=2017-04-02}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldepuebla/notas/n3246063.htm|title=Organización Editorial Mexicana|website=www.oem.com.mx|language=en|access-date=2017-04-02}}</ref>

With the end of the Classic Period, the nomadic [[Chichimeca|Chichimecas]] begin migrating into the modern day [[Valley of Mexico]] around the year 1200. From then on, Yohualican would come under pressure from these migratory tribes and would begin to fall into a gradual decline.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />

